{
  "plan_analysis": "The Home Office time-series dataset is the official resolution source, but forecasters still need:  \n\u2022 Base rates \u2013 how many people arrived by small boat between 1 Jan \u2013 30 Apr in prior years (2022-2025) and how those years ended overall.  \n\u2022 Current state \u2013 the exact cumulative total for 2026 up to \u201ctoday\u201d (6 Mar 2026) and the most recent daily figures to judge momentum.  \n\u2022 Key drivers \u2013 forthcoming weather/sea conditions in the Dover Strait, status of U.K. deterrence measures (Rwanda scheme, French patrol funding, new legislation) and migrant \u201csupply\u201d levels around Calais/Dunkirk.  \n\u2022 Resolution mechanism \u2013 confirmation that the small_boats_time_series.ods file is still published, what its structure is, and where the 2026 rows/columns live.  \n\u2022 Contrarian signals \u2013 evidence that crossings could be unusually low (e.g., severe storms, major enforcement operations) or unusually high (e.g., conflict-driven surges, legal blockage of deterrence policies).\n\nThe eight queries below pull:\n1-3) the official dataset and historical Jan-Apr subtotals for 2022-2025;  \n4-5) the freshest 2026 cumulative/daily numbers and channel-crossing news;  \n6-8) forward-looking information on policy, weather, and migrant staging that could materially swing the April total.",
